title: Anet A8 Brackets to Reduce X-Axis Motion

description.text:
These brackets are designed for the Anet A8 printer with the goal of reducing X-axis motion particularly when printing in higher reigns of the printer.
To mount the brackets you will need to dismantle the display screen and remove the 4 pillar washers as they will not be needed. Place each bracket in the corners of the frame, remount the display screen and additionally fixate the brackets to the side support plates with M3x0 mm screws. Make sure the brackets are placed flat on the frame plates. It might be necessary to clean up the holes in the brackets to get a clean fit, depending on the quality of the print and the tolerances of your frame.

Important notice!

It seems newer models have been revised on the left side.
If you measure 68-69mm then use file "Anet_A8_Top_Left_Bracket_Leo.stl"
If you measure 72-73mm the use file "Top_Left_Frame_Bracket_Plus3mm_Leo.stl"

When mounting the brackets you must loosen the "screws" first. Mount the brackets as shown and fixate to the frame. Lastly re-tighten the "screws".

Read the whole text carefully. View all pictures for reference! Do not print these brackets if your printer dimensions differ!

Please let me know if you have a problem with the design so I can improve it if necessary or you what new features to the design.

Also please post a picture with comments if you have made one.

Thanks.

Leo

Update 2016.11.21
  • For those wanting to use a spool holder on top the frame with these brackets may want to try these: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1908880
Update 2017.01.15
  • User "BlackChart" had asked if I could add a panel to the right bracket. He provided the part as sketch for me. You can mount an ON/OFF switch and a switch for lights. The holes have a diameter of 5mm and can be enlarged by drilling a bigger hole.
Update 2017.05.16
  • For those wanting the ultimate solution: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2189694

comments.text: The biggest drawback is material. The reason these Anets are so cheap is because they're all acrylic. description.text:
UPDATE: I would highly recommend to print the new and better 220 version of this frame,

This is a frame for a freestyle/racing sized quadcopter. It is designed to be an insanely fast, lightweigth and aerodynamic frame, while still enduring hard crashes. The frame can be printed without support on 200mm*200mm printbeds. It fits standard 2205/2204 motors and electronics with 30.5mm mounting hole spacing, making it compatible with most racing quadcopter equipment.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

P802M

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

95%

Notes:

Baseframe
This part needs to be printed in a strong and rigid material. While PLA will work, it’s brittle and will snap on very hard crashes, but otherwise the quadcopter will fly well. ABS, what I have used, works really well, other materials worth considering are PETG, nylon or polycarbonate if you can print those.

If you are printing ABS, acetone smoothing is highly recommendable. It increases the strengthening of layer bonds via the reduction of surface stress concentrations.

I didn’t have a large enough container to smooth the frame, so I painted on a mixture of acetone and ABS plastic.

I used 95% triangular infill, with five shells, top and bottom layers for maximum strength.

Aeoropod

This part would ideally be printed with a flexible material like TPU or TPE, but I don’t have that and printed it in PLA. That has worked well so far. You need support for the screw holders, and these needs to be added manually to not get support structure all over the part, as this is not needed.

This is the parts I would recommend if you want to enter the world of miniquads on a budget.

Motors: BR2205-2300KV

ESCs: RS20A-V2

Flight controller: Naze 32

PDB: Matek PDB

Propellers: Kingkong-5040-5x4x3-3-Blade

Nylon spacer screws

Battery straps

FPV Gear

You can fly the quadcopter without the fpv gear, but it is highly recommended to use it.

Camera: I have designed the pod for the RunCam PZ0420M camera.

VTX: Eachine ET526 5.8G 40CH 25mW200mW600mW Switchable FPV Transmitter

Antenna: Aomway 5.8GHz FPV 4 Leaf Clover AV Transmission RHCP Antenna

Misc

For a transmitter I would recommend getting a Taranis X9D PLUS, it's a fantastic transmitter that you can use for years. If you have a tight budget, get the FS i6, but you will most likely want something better pretty soon.

4s batteries are absolutely recommended, the Infinity Graphene are great and cheap.

description.text:
I tried my hand at designing a construction set for my daughters. This is by far my best design for the 3d printer and after countless hours of printing and tuning there it was.

After that, for a little while, greed got the better of me and slowly I came to realize the fun part was over and that everything pointed to this never seeing the light of day. Everything pointed wrong because today it sees the light of day :).

I tried to make it as simple as possible and it has just four basic elements, a node and beam for the rectangular structure and another node and beam for the roof structure. I made three other additional elements for stairs and walls/ceilings but many other could be done...for example a rectangular orifice in the ceiling element for doors and windows and even some finishes for the exterior of the structure.

The cool thing about it is that the more you print, the more intricate the structures, you can make out of it, become and the more the kids seem to love it.

I named it in memory of my late father, Mihai Eugen, who was a great structural engineer. He designed high rises, I designed this... :)
Thank you and I hope you will enjoy this set as much as my kids and myself do.
All the best
Mihai Filip

description.text:
This is a photo frame designed so that a number can be connected together and hung vertically. One of the gallery photos shows our 9 grandchildren in one vertical display.
The part of this project that took longest was working out a convenient was to connect the photo frames together.
But first a little about the photo frame. I didn't want anything to do with glass. What does the glass do? Keep the photo clean - not worried about that, and always print another - and keep the photo flat. This I covered by making room for the photo to be stuck to a piece of card with thin double sided foam tape.
The recess for the photo is sized for a square photo cut from 6" x 4" (102 x 152 mm) photo paper.
I've designed three variants of hanging and connecting brackets. One is fixed using 3 mm x 10 long screws, The screw connectors are good for easily removing one photo frame with little risk of damage.
The second type is based on split collets. These tend to break on assembly. BTW I used Diamond Age PLA for all components. If you want to use the collet type I suggest heating them up a bit by 10 to 20 secs in hot water from the tap - not boiling water.
The third type is a jam fit. stl files with different amount of interference are included. The hole size is 6.0 mm, and the fittings come with 6.0, 6.1 and 6.2 options (labelled 60, 61 & 62).
BTW some of the photos show earlier incarnations of the photo frame.
Note also that the 'mat' that keeps the photo in place is available 'plain' or with 2013 'engraved' in it.

The frame should be stood upright for printing and I recommend using a brim.
As mentioned in the description the collet type fittings probably need heating up in hot (but NOT boiling) water for 10 or 20 seconds.

This is a mount for the Z axis Microswitch for the Creatbot DX printer.

The default mount is somewhat lacking with respect to adjusting the Z axis home position. Two M3 bolts pass through the back panel of the printer, and the idea is to undo the bolts, physically move these up/down, and then retighten to set the home position of the Z axis microswitch. Whilst this works fine, it is a bit amateurish and if you do what I did and remove either bolt, when you re-insert it the nut which it is supposed to screw into falls out, and you are faced with major disassembly of the printer to recover the situation.

As I had to do this reassembly anyway I decided to replace the default microswitch mount with a new mount. Plus I figured I would replace the lever microswitch with a roller version (shown in the photograph), the reference details of which are shown on the following web page:

https://uk.rs-online.com/web/p/microswitches/0320528/

The mounting of the microswitch onto this mount is by M2.5 25mm bolts, which screw directly into the plastic. These bolts are a tight fit so I didn't need to use nuts to hold the microswitch.

Note that this mount can also support "regular" microswitches - the mounting holes are printed in the design. So you could choose to use regular microswitches instead.

The other components you will need are 2x flanged M3 rivnuts, and 2x M3 25mm bolts - adding M3 star lock washers might be a good idea.

Once assembled this mount installs similarly to the factory supplied mount, but with the bolts passing through the printer back panel passing through a simple platform on the back of the printer. This is a bit more positive than the factory supplied arrangement, and I believe easier to adjust.

title: Geared 1.75mm Bowden Feeder for 3D Printer (suitable for Flexible filament)

description.text:
I've built (and designed) my own Delta Printer, wanting something better than the current crop within my price range. Initially I bought a cheap aluminium feeder - which turned out to be less than ideal! It's main issue was that the filament path was not straight and not guided as it passed through the body. If too much pushing force is applied, the filament buckles and the print is ruined!

On my original (Ultimaker) I printed an iRoberti feeder, which is excellent! However, there didn't seem to be a 1.75 version which used the push-fit connectors for bowden tube. I figured, if I had to modify it, I might as well start from scratch!

Originally I used this with a regular NEMA17 motor - which worked fine. The parts pictured were printed using it (in PolyMax filament). I want to push the speed of my printer and a standard NEMA17 just doesn't seem to develop the torque I require. Instead, I'm using a NEMA17 with a 5:1 reduction gearbox - so about 5x the torque. However, this will work just as well geared or not.

In addition to the motor, you need:
4 x M3 x 25mm screws
4 x M3 Nyloc Nuts (Plain nuts will just loosen within minutes!)
1 x 22mm OD, 8mm ID, 7mm Thick bearing (608-ZZ type (ZZ just means metal shields as they run more freely than 2RS type, rubber shields)
1 x Drive Gear suitable for your motor (*See Below)
1 x 4mm, M6 Push Fit connector for Bowden tube.
1 x 9mm OD 20-25mm long spring (from an eBay spring assortment)
1 x M4 x 16 Screw (for tension adjustment)
1 x M4 Plain Nut (for tension adjustment)
(Optional)
Short length of 3mm OD Bowden tube to guide the filament in.

And, of course a 3D Printer to print the bits!

The Drive Gear must be no more than 12.5mm OD. Most of the Mk7 & Mk8 types are suitable. Most motors have a 5mm or 6mm shaft (you'll have to measure) whereas my geared motor has an 8mm shaft. My 8mm bore gear has not arrived yet which is why it's missing in the photos!

Part 'Stepper Mount Temp.STL' is designed to mount on to my printer - but you should be able to adapt this to yours, if it's needed at all. The four inner holes are correct for the geared NEMA17. The four outer ones for an ordinary NEMA17 motor.

The filament is guided all the way through, apart from about 1mm either side of the drive gear. I've found it works well with PolyFlex and NinjaFlex - so probably most of the others too.

I heated up the tip of an M6 bolt (with a lighter) and screwed that in first to melt a thread - but if you're careful you can just screw it in letting it cut it's own thread as it goes.

The design incorporates a release 'switch' which pushes the bearing away from the filament and holds it released. Handy for manually loading filament.

I just used a random spring I found in an assortment bought from eBay years ago. It needs to be no more than 9mm OD and greater than 6mm bore. It doesn't need to be particularly strong. Mine is stronger than it needs to be.

I hope this proves useful! Feel free to share, distribute, hack!

title: Geeetech MK8 dual extruder plate for my Quick Fit Carriage

description.text:
A mounting plate for the Geeetech MK8 dual extruder made for my Quick Fit Carriage (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1670305). The fans and heat sinks have to be removed to fit the plate (they reduce Y-building volume by ~29mm and increase weight and torque of the carriage). Alternative cooling of the throat and the two motors is achieved by a air-duct system powered by a 50mm blower. On each side mounting holes for M3 screws and nuts are present to allow for fixation of bed-level sensors. These holes have a separation of 26mm. I made the blower-attachment removable. I'll add a 40mm fan version later.

Used dimension of the mounting bracket: 86.0mm x 10mm x 15.5mm.

Because I do not have a dual extruder, I cannot check if everything is OK. There are no CAD-data-sheets available for the extruder.

Thanks to Tombhunter for manifold and valuable bug-fixing input.

Notes:

A version with and without manually designed support is provided. Please select proper printing orientation: The flat side is down. The manually designed supports indicate proper printing orientation.

description.text:
It's a project box, tub with a lid and specific mounting holes and bosses to hold the stuff.

This box fits on the build-plate, barely, I've done one build ~24 hours for the box, ~8 hours for the lid.

Enterprising OpenSCAD designers should be able to lift parts from it for their own designs. I think the honeycomb texture is helping with shrinkage and stubborn removal issues, though it was still pretty hard for me to remove the box from the build plate. Compared to a 4"x4" flat bottomed build I just did, this hex pattern is indeed easier to get off the plate, but I discovered a new technique that makes even flat bottom prints easy to remove: heat the build plate to 130C and slide the spatula in under the soft ABS... seems to work every time.

The texture, and torus shapes, seem to be too much for the Customizer, it's giving script timeouts. Try the .scad file with OpenSCAD on your own computer, and have a little patience with the rendering times.

Printer:

FlashForge Dreamer

Resolution:

.18

Infill:

15%

Notes:

3 shells, otherwise standard settings (3 top and bottom layers, all standard temps and speeds). If I print it again, I might go for higher extruder temp on the box - there was a little bit of layer separation, probably because of the size and cooling between layers.

Hairspray on the build plate, check and recheck level before walking away. The first layer of print should give you a very good idea if you are at correct level.

You might get away with PLA in the box, I would definitely recommend ABS in the lid. I printed both in ABS, they snap together very securely, I doubt that PLA would flex enough to go together with the current dimensions.

I wanted a box...

At first I was trying to make a custom sized box to just hold the components I'm planning, but that size was within an inch or so of my build platform limits anyway, so I expanded the footprint to near the build plate's limits and just give a little extra space inside to make wire packing easier.

The round face corners are primarily to give a little style to the box, and also reflect the fact that I have big power supply bricks to go in the back and a Raspberry Pi that's not so big to go in the front.

The honeycomb texture is an experimental idea to help with shrinkage problems and also make the big flat plates easier to remove at the end of the build.

I might try changing the zip-tie bosses to cutouts from the walls in the future, but for now I thought that they would work better/easier being a straight pass through instead of trying to get the zip-tie to flex and push through a potentially "stringy" curved hole.

The overhangs are all sloped to eliminate the need for any support material.

description.text:
A Dream Come True: Bela Merda means Beautiful Poop in brazilian portuguese and it is exactly that, a customizable piece of shit for your appreciation. While it might seem a bad attempt at a joke is actually useful, feces have a huge symbolic value on our culture so you might use this base design to convoy a bunch of negative conotations. You can make a trophy out of it to someone you feel to be full of shit, you can offer this as a gift to Murphy the God to get protection from bad situations, you can repurpose it and maybe an anaconda body or any other archimedean spiral design you wish. You can also post-edit it in Blender and add a rougher surface and use cura's fuzzy skin feature to print it more realistically.

Speaking of archimedean spiral, this is trivial to make in 3D modelling software like Blender (add curve -> spiral -> archimedean spiral, set the right parameters, use it as a path for a cone or phallus-shaped cylinder, etc.), and the implementation is quite inefficient in OpenSCAD (a bunch of concatenated sphere hulls), so it takes forever to render. You might even not want to wait for render finish on the customizer window and ask to create it altogether, or just download the .scad file and change the variables yourself.

description.text:
A dummy AA-battery allows you to 'short out' one position in a battery pack so that you can get a different voltage. For example, if you have a four-cell pack and want to power a circuit with 4.5 volts rather than 6 volts, you can replace one of the cells with a dummy battery.

Another use: you could connect a power-supply into a battery pack with one of these. Just ensure you get your polarities right, and you probably need a few dummies for the other position(s) in your pack. Don't use an external power-supply AND a real battery together. That's a bad idea.

I wasn't the first one to think of this, and I found a couple of other designs on Thingiverse for it as well, but they were all missing some nuance that I wanted in my design. And given that it's just a cylinder, it's a pretty quick thing to throw together.

I made my first pass a bit better, and it works so well that I decided to share it here.

You simply string a wire through it, and loop through the holes like sewing a button and you get a good contact in most battery holders.

I looped through the positive (bump) end 3-times with 22-gauge wire and a 'Z' pattern on the negative (flat) end. Works for me.

Need a AAA battery? You can probably scale it if you wish.

I used a raft with 4mm extra size to ensure I got good adhesion. With a tall item I wanted to be sure It didn't flop over half way through and make a mess. Go without if you are confident in your bed-adhesion.

Wiring it up.

You can use any old wire laying around. I just stripped the ends, but really insulation on the inside bits doesn't really add any value. Don't go with too small of a gauge - remember you can get a fair bit of current out of a AA battery and you don't want it to go 'open' on you.

Oh here's a thought you could use super-fine wire and it could be a fuse?

A pair of tweezers or fine needle-nose pliers are useful for helping you with the threading.

description.text: Fully printable set of 4" dial calipers. It has 9 separate moving parts and can be printed as one complete assembly or in pieces. The smallest gaps between separate pieces are about 0.010", so if you want to print this as one complete assembly make sure your printer can support this and can print modeling and support material together. Alternatively, you can scale up the design to increase the gap size or print out the pieces and assemble it by hand. I haven't tried assembling this from the separate pieces but it should go together with a little hand work and super glue. If you find that there is too much friction to move the calipers try applying a plastic-safe grease to the gear teeth and gear faces. I used a little Crisco cooking grease for this and it worked very well. Calipers include inside & outside jaws, depth gauge, adjustable & locking dial, and thumb wheel. I actually found the precision in measurement to be surprisingly accurate. With a little care you can get correct measurements to within +/-0.0025". This was printed on an Objet Eden Printer. Scale STLs to 78.74% of original size to convert to metric. More Info: http://thecornercase.blogspot.com/2014/03/3d-printed-dial-calipers.html Video: http://youtu.be/QP7harBuc-Q

description.text: My K2 "Alexis" inline skates came with a brake pad bolted on to the shaft of the rear skate on the right foot. After a fall where my ribs were severely bruised by the brake shoved in to my back, I decided I'd be better off without it. So I unbolted the rear wheel and took it off, but the axel shaft is too long and was left loose without the brake attached. These spacers help make sure the skate frame grips the bearings properly and their taper helps keep the bolt heads from catching on anything. Made with Oozby - my OpenSCAD preprocessor, makes neat use of corner_radius option on cylinder() for nicer aesthetics.

Print off two. I printed mine in generic black PLA using 20 shells (effectively making the whole thing out of solid shells). Because these need to be under a bit of pressure from the bolts, I recommend printing them solid or close to it.  
I don't think you need to fuss over materials too much with this. If they break the skates still work and are safe - they're just a tad more likely to catch on something and trip you up. Still I think it's a good idea to print it solid, with heaps of shells. Nice strong spirals.

title: CASE for the Raspberry Pi + TFT LCD-Touch-Display 800x480 laser cut

description.text:
Assembly video: https://youtu.be/wOMzah51rM0

Deutsche Anleitung untenstehend!

The assembly of this Raspberry case is shown in the video.
A 17.8 cm (7") TFT LCD touch display (800 x 480 pixels) is used. The case is compatible with it.
The special thing is that the orientation of the Raspi is lengthwise. The USB connectors and the network connector can be accessed from the outside. There are no more openings for this purpose in the case so in order to access other connectors additional openings which are already in the case have to be used instead. As an alternative, you can also add them to the plans. When the Raspberry Pi is used as an OBD2 computer the vehicle provides the power directly via the Diamex-OBD-HAT (5V)—for the Raspi as well as the Foundation’s touch display. So in this example there is no additional power supply included.
The front and back are made of 3mm acrylic (laser-cut).
The aluminum pieces (i.e. the side frame) are made of 11cm long aluminum profiles GB77 (Fischer-Elektronik www.fischerelektronik.de).
After the assembly the case is very stable.
An OBD2-HAT by Diamex is used in this example. Of course, you can also use other HAT hardware for the Raspberry. (http://www.diamex.de/dxshop/PI-OBD-HAT-OBD2-Modul-fuer-Raspberry-PI)
The case can be acquired here:
http://www.diamex.de/dxshop/Profi-Gehaeuse-Bausatz

Deutsche Anleitung:

Der Zusammenbau des Raspberry Gehäuses im Video veranschaulicht.
Es kommt das 17,8 cm (7") TFT LCD-Touch-Display, 800 x 480 Pixel
zum Einsatz. Dafür ist das Gehäuse ausgelegt.
Die Besonderheit ist, dass das Raspi längs eingebaut ist. Die USB-Anschlüsse und die Netzwerkbuchse sind von außen zugänglich. Andere Anschlüsse müssen möglicherweise separat herausgeführt werden. In der Anwendung als OBD2-Computer wird die Stromversorgung vom Pkw geliefert und direkt über das Diamex-OBD-HAT aufbereitet, für den Raspi sowohl auch für das Touchdisplay der Foundation. If, like me you have some electric wires to hide.

I needed to modify an Ikea METOD kitchen cabinet, and wanted to use the standard Ikea style fixation, witch is a strong fixation for my usage. The issue for this fixation is that they need precise drilled hole alignement. So I designed drill guide that let me align these with a precision way below mm precision.

The guides are quite quick to print if you use .35 layers, and are made to be disposable after several usage, being easily damaged by the drill process.

You will need Ikea screws and 3 drills, a 5 mm drill, a 8 mm drill and a flat 15 mm drill.

There are 3 guides, calibrated to position the holes for Ikea standard 19 mm plank .

The process is described by the pictures.

Step 1:

  • Position the plancks and mark the position of the holes with a pencil..

Step 2:

  • Align and position guide-5 on the main plank, using the slit to perfectly align with the pencil mark.
  • Use a scotch tape to mark the maximum depth on the 5 mm drill
  • Use a clamp to fix the guide 5
  • Drill a 5 mm hole, watch the scotch tape on the drill to ensure not to drill too deep.

Step 3:

  • Align and position the guide-15 on the second plank, using the lit to perfectly align with the pencil mark.
  • Use a scotch tape to mark the maximum depth of the 15 mm drill
  • Use a clamp to fix the guide 15
  • Drill a 15 mm hole, watch the scotch tape on the drill to ensure not to drill too deep.

Step 4:

  • Align and position the guide 8 on the second plank, using the slit to perfectly align with the pencil mark.
  • Use a clamp to fix the guide 8
  • Drill a 8 mm hole up to the 15 mm hole

Step 5:

  • Assemble the screws.

Step 6:

  • Admire the result and open a beer to be happy :)

title: Spacer Mounting Plate for Triple MOSFET board/module

description.text:
This is a spacer for use in mounting one of the triple MOSFET switch modules available on eBay. Listings come and go, but the current listing title contains the text "MOSFET breakout board module switch relay (15A, 60V) 3-outputs for Arduino/RPi". These modules provide three MOSFET switches that can be used with a 3D printer, Arduino, Raspberry Pi, or other electronic application where higher DC voltage or current switching is required than the microcontroller can support.

The modules have two mounting holes on one edge. Unfortunately, if the module is mounted with spacers or standoffs on those two holes, the other side of the board can flex when mating the control cable connector or tightening screws on the power input terminal block. This design provides a 6mm tall riser block that is sized to match the dimensions and corner radius of the MOSFET module, with the intent that it supports the entire board, not just one edge.

The STL file should be useable as-is. If tailoring is desired, you'll also have to download the roundedCornerCube.scad file from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:8812. Download the mosfet_bracket.scad file and edit the line with the correct path location if you don't use the CUSTOM library folder for the roundedCornerCase file. Locate and edit the parameters requiring changes, render, and generate a new STL file.

NOTE: The spacer was designed and used with a Mosfet module marked as v1.1, although eBay seller madeatrade has indicated the spacer plate should also work with newer versions of the triple MOSFET module.

12/31 UPDATE: Found out the hard way that the first thing that breaks is the "G" on the King's crown.

I made two new versions - one with a much sturdier "G", and one with a conventional crown, but with a large "G" on the King's chest.

These are both attached now.

I liked the chess set from Steve, but the first couple I printed had fragile arms and seemed a bit small for the resolution.

I revised to put the arms close to the body or holding something, and that seemed to work out ok. For the King, I extended his staff and enlarged the platform so I could anchor the staff.

I then scaled all up to 125% of original, and for me, it looks better.

Thanks, Steve!

title: Folger Tech Kossel Belt Guard & Corner Opening Cover Plate

description.text:
Update 11/8/2016
After printing this again for the left side with the cable, this side was 2mm longer opening, so I made a Long & a Short version. I also realized their are 2 nice holes on the aluminum vertex to wire tie these in place instead of using a T-Nut. You can see a 8" black wire tie on the left cover of the 1st photo. There are still a number of options in the openscad file if you prefer to print it a little differently. I also allowed 2mm more clearance in front of the belts.

I would suggest printing VerticalBelt_GuardShortTest_Rev12.stl file 1st to see how well it fits on each of 3 vertices.

I occasionally have something fall thru these openings and sometimes plastic debris gets caught in the belts, so I came up with this idea. I have included an openscad file & 4 stl files. There are 2 T-Nut screw holes on each side, but it was a tight enough fit on my machine that I do not need them. In the openscad file you can set a few variables, like the base height, Belt Guard height & opening for Effector cables. I set the base height at 2mm & height for the belt guard at 30mm, but you can go to what ever height you want.

I have only tested this on an hour print & not sure if there needs to be some ventilation holes for heat from the motors so I added an option for putting in heat vents above the motors if anyone has problems with heat not venting.
